adjectives.description: multitudinous (comparative more multitudinous, superlative most multitudinous)

entries.meaning: Existing in great numbers; innumerable. [from 17th c.]
examples: In the multitudinous whimseys of a disabled mind and body, the thick-coming fancies often occur to me that the events which affect my life and adventures are specially shaped to disappoint my purposes.

entries.meaning: Comprising a large number of parts.
examples: […]  he feared no enemies but the Sea and the Earth; the one yeelding no safe harbour for such a Navie; the other not yeelding sufficient sustenance for so multitudinous an Armie.
The transport of a fierce and monstrous gladnessSpread thro’ the multitudinous streets, fast flyingUpon the winds of fear  […]

entries.meaning: Coming from or produced by a large number of beings or objects.
examples: […]  she paused before she opened the doors of the salon, for a loud and confused noise came from within. It was of a kind that she had never heard before, so happy it was, so multitudinous, so abandoned—the sound of voices at play.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Of or relating to the multitude, of the common people.
